[4] USA (CDC alert)
Date: Fri 19 Dec 2014
Source: HCP Live [edited]
http://www.hcplive.com/articles/CDC-Measles-Cases-at-Airport-Highlight-Ease-of-Transmission


Traveling through the same US airport gate, one infected passenger transmitted measles virus to 3 others within a 4-hour time span, illustrating just how easily the virus can spread. These findings were reported in the 19 Dec 2014 issue of the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report. The measles "cluster" of cases originated at one gate at an unnamed US international airport, according to the report. Transmission likely occurred on Fri 17 Jan 2014. The gate in question was located in a terminal that only serviced domestic flights.

The 1st patient outlined in the report was a 21-year-old man. He developed a measles rash on 1 Feb 2014 and had traveled on 2 domestic flights that connected at the airport about 2 weeks beforehand, on 17 and 18 Jan 2014. Patient 2 was a 49-year-old man who also developed a measles rash on 1 Feb 2014. He had reported traveling from the airport on 17 Jan 2014. A 3rd patient, aged 19, came down with the measles rash on 30 Jan 2014. He said he had spent 4 hours on a layover in the airport on 17 Jan 2014 as well. Finally, patient 4, a 63-year-old man, developed a measles rash on 5 Feb 2014. He had also traveled through the airport on 17 Jan 2014.

"The exposures in this report were not prolonged and occurred in a domestic rather than an international terminal, highlighting the fact that measles is highly contagious," the authors write. They stressed that: "Measles continues to pose a risk for infection among unvaccinated persons in the United States."

None of the 4 people infected had been vaccinated.

